<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-10-11T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-10-11T03:00:00-05:00" n="339" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d339">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5605: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-10-11T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 11,
                                        1924—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 11—6:18
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>383. Marshal Wu Pei-fu left Peking early this morning to direct
                            operations at the northern front. Colonel Barnard and Captain
                                Woodbridge<note n="11" xml:id="d339fn11">U. S. Army officers
                                attached to the Legation in China.</note> accompanied him as
                            observers at his invitation. British, French and Japanese officers also
                            accompanied Wu in like capacity.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>